diff:1293852325:1293852325:=1,68d0%0a%3c (:Summary::)%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  Although "I Think, Therefore I Am" was the line on which Descartes%0a%3c achieved his meteoric rise to stardom, that was not the line he actually%0a%3c wrote.  So I can't tell you how much pleasure it gives me to put the%0a%3c record straight, if only for poor Rene's sake.%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  You may well wonder how it was that Rene managed to reach Number%0a%3c One among philosophy's all-time chart-toppers.  Well, as I've indicated,%0a%3c it was all due to the widespread misunderstanding about his line "I%0a%3c Think, Therefore I Am".  And to trace the EXACT origin of that I must%0a%3c take you, by the magic of radio, back to the New Year's Eve party which%0a%3c Madame Descartes threw to celebrate the advent of 1636.%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  She'd decided that as it was to be an informal affair what she'd%0a%3c serve would be a "buffet" (a French word meaning "we've got more people%0a%3c than chairs").  As she also intended it to be a late do, with the guests%0a%3c not arriving until around 11 o'clock, she ran up an enormous bunch of%0a%3c that Gallic imitation of bacon-and-egg flan they call "Quiches".%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  However, Madame made it clear to Rene that although the quiches%0a%3c would be put out on the sideboard in advance -- "what I DON'T want is%0a%3c people helping themselves all evening and treading their crumbs into the%0a%3c Aubusson.  So I'm relying on you to see to it that nobody starts digging%0a%3c into them until at least an hour after we've seen the New Year in.  Then%0a%3c they can take plates and eat properly!"%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  Ironic, isn't it?  The founder of the Cartesian School relegated%0a%3c to the position of Securicor for bacon-and-egg flans.  As he said to%0a%3c Father Dinet -- I haven't mentioned him, but he was a Jesuit priest%0a%3c who was about Rene's only real mate at that time -- as he said to him,%0a%3c "I can't think this is in any way advancing my career.  Being sat down%0a%3c here at the sideboard till one o'clock in the morning, no way will there%0a%3c be any philosophising done tomorrow.  I'll be like a limp rag."%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  To which the good Father rejoined an extremely practical rejoiner.%0a%3c "Then why don't you use this as WORKING time?  Take a pen and write%0a%3c while you're sitting here, set your mind for lofty thoughts and if any%0a%3c arrive, jot them down ona paper serviette.%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  "Not a bad idea at all," said Descartes.  "Give us a borrow of%0a%3c your quill."%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  So it was that for the next hour or so, there by the sideboard%0a%3c the two friends sat and Descartes was able to get off quite a few%0a%3c zingers relating to corporeal rationality.  It was while he was putting%0a%3c into shape an eternal verity on adventitious volition that he glanced%0a%3c up and, to his horror, saw that Father Dinet had absent-mindedly helped%0a%3c himself to a quiche and was quietly munching it.%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  About to open his mouth and exclaim "watch it!" They're not supposed%0a%3c to be eaten yet," he became aware of something else.  There, not two%0a%3c yards away -- well within earshot -- stood his wife!!%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  There was only one thing to do.  Stealthily, Descartes took another%0a%3c serviette, scribbled out his warning, then equally furtively, pushed%0a%3c the serviette under Father Dinet's nose.%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  So it was that the whole 300-year-old misunderstanding originated.%0a%3c That message -- the one which Father Dinet was later to publish to the%0a%3c world as "I Think Therefore I Am" -- all it referred to was the time-ban%0a%3c on the bacon-and-egg flans.%0a%3c %0a%3c 	  The truth is, what Descartes actually wrote was I THINK THEY'RE%0a%3c FOR 1 A.M.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25rframe%25 '''Categories:''' [[!Humour]]%0a
